SCOPE

PRIB 2013:
The International Association of Pattern Recognition (IAPR) sponsored
conference aims to bring together top researchers, practitioners and
students from around the world to discuss the applications of pattern
recognition methods in the field of bioinformatics to solve problems in the
life sciences. Prospective authors are invited to submit papers in the
research areas of interest to the workshop. These include, but not limited
to:

=E2=80=A2    Bio-sequence analysis
=E2=80=A2    Gene and protein expression analysis
=E2=80=A2    Protein structure and interaction prediction
=E2=80=A2    Motifs and signal detection
=E2=80=A2    Metabolic modeling and analysis
=E2=80=A2    Systems and synthetic biology
=E2=80=A2    Pathway and network analysis
=E2=80=A2    Immuno- and chemo-informatics
=E2=80=A2    Evolution and phylogeny
=E2=80=A2    Biological databases, integration and visualization
=E2=80=A2    Bio-imaging
=E2=80=A2    Eco-informatics
=E2=80=A2    Network Systems Biology

Pattern recognition techniques of interest include, but not limited to:

=E2=80=A2    Static, syntactic and structural pattern recognition
=E2=80=A2    Data mining, Data based modeling
=E2=80=A2    Neural networks, Fuzzy systems
=E2=80=A2    Evolutionary computation and swarm intelligence
=E2=80=A2    Hidden Markov models, Graphical models

CIBB 2013:
The main goal of CIBB meetings is to provide a forum open to researchers
from different disciplines to present and discuss problems concerning
computational techniques in bioinformatics, systems biology, and medical
and health informatics with a particular focus on Neural Networks, Machine
Learning, Fuzzy Logic, and Evolutionary Computation methods. Technical
areas addressed by CIBB 2013 include, but are not limited to:

=E2=80=A2    Sequence analysis, promoter analysis and identification of
transcription
=E2=80=A2    Factor binding sites
=E2=80=A2    Gene expression data analysis
=E2=80=A2    Methods for the integration of clinical and genetic data
=E2=80=A2    Algorithms for alternative splicing analysis
=E2=80=A2    Methods for functional classification of genes
=E2=80=A2    Methods for unsupervised analysis, validation and visualizatio=
n of
=E2=80=A2    Structures discovered in bio-molecular data
=E2=80=A2    Prediction of secondary and tertiary protein structures
=E2=80=A2    Mass spectrometry data analysis in proteomics
=E2=80=A2    Methods for comparative genomics
=E2=80=A2    Algorithms for molecular evolution and phylogenetic analysis
=E2=80=A2    Mathematical modeling and simulation of biological systems
=E2=80=A2    Heterogeneous data integration and data fusion for diagnostics
=E2=80=A2    Bio-molecular databases and data mining
=E2=80=A2    Algorithms for pharmacogenomics
=E2=80=A2    Biomedical text mining and imaging
=E2=80=A2    Methods for diagnosis and prognosis
=E2=80=A2    Software tools for bioinformatics
=E2=80=A2    Health-Informatics and Medical Informatics.

CIBB 2013 is jointly organized by:

=E2=80=A2    INNS International Neural Network Society SIG Bioinformatics
=E2=80=A2    INNS International Neural Network Society SIG Bio-pattern
=E2=80=A2    IEEE-CIS-BBCT Task forces on Neural Networks and Evolutionary
Computation
=E2=80=A2    University of Nice Sophia Antipolis, France
=E2=80=A2    Dipartimento di Informatica =E2=80=93 University of Salerno, I=
taly

with the sponsorship of:

=E2=80=A2    SIREN: Italian Neural Networks Society
=E2=80=A2    RNBIO: The Italian Network for Oncology Bioinformatics
=E2=80=A2    ANR EMC project, Nice, France
=E2=80=A2    I3S Laboratory, Sophia Antipolis, France
=E2=80=A2    R=C3=A9gion PACA, France
=E2=80=A2    ED STIC, Universit=C3=A9 Nice Sophia Antipolis, France
=E2=80=A2    Dipartimento di Informatica =E2=80=93 University of Salerno (I=
taly)

The scientific programs of PRIB-CIBB 2013 will include five Keynote
Speakers, tutorial sessions, and contributed papers that will be presented
in plenary oral sessions, special sessions, or poster sessions.

